<!-- Modal JavaScript -->
<script>
function openModal(articleId) {
    var modal = document.getElementById('modalOverlay');
    var body = document.getElementById('modalBody');
    if (articleId === 'professionalEthics') {
        body.innerHTML = `
            <h2>Professional Ethics & Professional Accounting System</h2>
            <h3>Navigating the Ethical Labyrinth: A Critical Analysis of Advocates' Duties When Defending Guilty Clients in the Indian Legal System</h3>
            <p>
                <strong>Submitted to:</strong> Dr. Shreemanshu Kumar Dash, Assistant Professor, Law, NUSRL, Ranchi<br>
                <strong>Submitted by:</strong> Himanshu, Roll No.: 1108, Semester: X-A
            </p>
            <h4>Abstract</h4>
            <p>
                The ethical dilemma of defending clients believed to be guilty represents one of the most profound challenges confronting the legal profession in India. This research article critically examines the complex intersection of professional duties, moral obligations, and legal imperatives that advocates must navigate when representing clients whose guilt they suspect or know. Through comprehensive analysis of statutory provisions, professional conduct rules, landmark case law, and ethical frameworks, this study explores how advocates balance their zealous advocacy obligations with their duties as officers of the court and guardians of justice.
            </p>
            <h4>Introduction</h4>
            <p>
                The cornerstone of any democratic legal system rests upon the fundamental principle that every accused person deserves competent legal representation, regardless of the nature of the charges against them or their apparent guilt or innocence. This principle, deeply embedded in the Indian Constitution through Article 22 and reinforced by the Advocates Act of 1961, creates a professional and moral imperative for advocates to represent all clients without prejudice. However, this noble obligation generates one of the most challenging ethical dilemmas in legal practice: how should advocates conduct themselves when they know or strongly suspect that their client is guilty of the charges against them?
            </p>
            <h4>Objectives</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Comprehensive analysis of ethical dilemmas when defending guilty clients.</li>
                <li>Examination of the legal framework (Advocates Act, Bar Council Rules, Constitution).</li>
                <li>Analysis of landmark cases and judicial guidance.</li>
                <li>Identify practical solutions and best practices.</li>
                <li>Propose regulatory reforms for ethical guidance.</li>
            </ul>
            <h4>Research Questions</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>How do advocates reconcile their duty with knowledge of client guilt?</li>
                <li>Are current rules adequate for these ethical complexities?</li>
                <li>How have courts interpreted and applied these principles?</li>
                <li>What practical strategies can advocates use to maintain ethics?</li>
            </ul>
            <h4>Key Sections</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Constitutional Foundations:</strong> Article 22 and the right to legal representation.</li>
                <li><strong>The Advocates Act of 1961:</strong> Professional obligations and dual roles.</li>
                <li><strong>Professional Conduct Rules:</strong> Duty to accept briefs, prohibition against misleading the court, confidentiality and its limits.</li>
                <li><strong>Case Law Analysis:</strong> Zahira Sheikh v. State of Gujarat and other landmark cases.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                <em>For the full article, please download the complete document below.</em>
            </p>
            <p>
                <a href="https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/attachments/63530037/7957ef9d-0d82-49b1-8446-eba8c3774f81/Professional-Ethics-Himanshu-1108.docx" target="_blank" style="color: #1a73e8; text-decoration: underline; font-weight: bold;">Download Full Document (DOCX)</a>
            </p>
        `;
    } else {
        // Placeholder for other articles
        body.innerHTML = "<p>Full article coming soon.</p>";
    }
    modal.style.display = 'flex';
}
function closeModal() {
    document.getElementById('modalOverlay').style.display = 'none';
}
</script>


