    <!-- Modals -->
    <div id="landPooling" class="modal">
        <div class="modal-content">
            <span class="close">&times;</span>
            <h2>The Land Pooling Paradox: Balancing Developer Incentives and Public Good in Delhi's Master Plan 2041</h2>
            <div class="meta">Urban Development Law • Policy Analysis • Published 2024</div>
            
            <h3>Abstract</h3>
            <p>Delhi, India's capital city, stands at a critical juncture in its urban development trajectory. As the second-largest urban agglomeration globally after Tokyo, Delhi faces unprecedented challenges in housing, infrastructure, and environmental sustainability. This comprehensive study examines the intricate balance between developer incentives and public welfare within Delhi's innovative Land Pooling Policy framework.</p>
            
            <h3>Key Research Questions</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>How does Delhi's Land Pooling Policy attempt to reconcile competing interests of developers, landowners, and the broader public interest within the legal framework of urban development?</li>
                <li>What are the key implementation challenges facing Delhi's land pooling mechanism, and how do they reflect broader tensions in urban governance?</li>
                <li>How do incentive structures embedded in MPD 2041, particularly Floor Area Ratio provisions, impact the balance between developer profits and public good objectives?</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Methodology</h3>
            <p>This study employs a mixed-methods approach combining legal analysis, policy document review, and comparative case study methodologies. The research process involved in-depth examination of relevant legislative frameworks, systematic comparison with successful models from other jurisdictions, and critical analysis of stakeholder perspectives and judicial precedents.</p>
            
            <h3>Key Findings</h3>
            <p>The implementation experience reveals substantial tensions between developer incentives and public welfare objectives, highlighting the need for careful recalibration of legal frameworks, institutional mechanisms, and incentive structures. The study identifies several structural impediments including fragmented ownership, contiguity problems, and limited institutional facilitation.</p>
            
            <h3>Comparative Analysis</h3>
            <p>The research provides insights from Gujarat's Town Planning Scheme and international models from Germany, Japan, and South Korea, offering valuable lessons for improving Delhi's approach through enhanced state facilitation, structured consultation processes, and responsive plan refinement mechanisms.</p>
            
            <h3>Policy Recommendations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Legislative reforms to address implementation bottlenecks</li>
                <li>Enhanced institutional coordination mechanisms</li>
                <li>Strengthened participation frameworks for stakeholders</li>
                <li>Balanced incentive structures aligning developer profits with public welfare</li>
                <li>Robust monitoring and evaluation systems</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="environmental" class="modal">
        <div class="modal-content">
            <span class="close">&times;</span>
            <h2>Constitutional Dimensions of Environmental Justice in Urban Planning</h2>
            <div class="meta">Constitutional Law • Environmental Law • Urban Policy</div>
            
            <h3>Research Overview</h3>
            <p>This research explores the intersection of constitutional principles and environmental protection in urban development, with specific focus on intergenerational equity and sustainable development doctrines in Indian jurisprudence.</p>
            
            <h3>Constitutional Framework</h3>
            <p>The study examines how constitutional provisions, particularly Articles 21 (Right to Life) and 48A (Protection of Environment), create binding obligations for urban planning authorities to consider environmental justice in development decisions.</p>
            
            <h3>Judicial Interpretation</h3>
            <p>Analysis of landmark cases including M.C. Mehta v. Union of India and their impact on establishing principles of sustainable development and intergenerational equity in urban planning law.</p>
            
            <h3>Policy Implications</h3>
            <p>The research identifies gaps in current urban planning frameworks and proposes constitutional law-based approaches to ensure environmental justice in urban development processes.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="comparative" class="modal">
        <div class="modal-content">
            <span class="close">&times;</span>
            <h2>Comparative Analysis of Land Assembly Mechanisms: Lessons from International Jurisprudence</h2>
            <div class="meta">Comparative Law • Property Rights • International Law</div>
            
            <h3>Comparative Framework</h3>
            <p>This comprehensive study examines land assembly mechanisms across different legal systems, analyzing the German, Japanese, and Indian approaches to balancing property rights with development imperatives.</p>
            
            <h3>Methodological Approach</h3>
            <p>The research employs comparative legal methodology to analyze institutional frameworks, procedural safeguards, and outcome effectiveness across different jurisdictions.</p>
            
            <h3>Key Jurisdictions Analyzed</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Germany's Land Readjustment System</li>
                <li>Japan's Land Pooling Initiatives</li>
                <li>South Korea's Urban Development Mechanisms</li>
                <li>India's Emerging Land Pooling Policies</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Findings and Recommendations</h3>
            <p>The study identifies best practices in stakeholder consultation, dispute resolution mechanisms, and institutional design that can inform policy development in emerging economies seeking to balance development imperatives with property rights protection.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Smooth scrolling and section visibility
        const observerOptions = {
            threshold: 0.1,
            rootMargin: '0px 0px -50px 0px'
        };

        const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
            entries.forEach(entry => {
                if (entry.isIntersecting) {
                    entry.target.classList.add('visible');
                }
            });
        }, observerOptions);

        document.querySelectorAll('.section').forEach(section => {
            observer.observe(section);
        });

        // Modal functionality
        function openModal(modalId) {
            document.getElementById(modalId).style.display = 'block';
            document.body.style.overflow = 'hidden';
        }

        document.querySelectorAll('.close').forEach(closeBtn => {
            closeBtn.onclick = function() {
                this.parentElement.parentElement.style.display = 'none';
                document.body.style.overflow = 'auto';
            }
        });

        window.onclick = function(event) {
            if (event.target.classList.contains('modal')) {
                event.target.style.display = 'none';
                document.body.style.overflow = 'auto';
            }
        }

        // Resume download functionality
        function downloadResume() {
            // In a real implementation, this would link to an actual PDF file
            alert('Resume download would be implemented with actual PDF file link.');
        }

        // Navigation highlighting
        window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
            let current = '';
            document.querySelectorAll('section').forEach(section => {
                const sectionTop = section.offsetTop;
                const sectionHeight = section.clientHeight;
                if (scrollY >= (sectionTop - 200)) {
                    current = section.getAttribute('id');
                }
            });

            document.querySelectorAll('.nav-links a').forEach(link => {
                link.classList.remove('active');
                if (link.getAttribute('href').substring(1) === current) {
                    link.classList.add('active');
                }
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
